"Kaiser C., Meyer H., Biasi C., Rusalimova O., Barsukov P., Richter A.","Storage and mineralization of carbon and nitrogen in soils of a frost-boil tundra ecosystem in Siberia",2005,"Applied Soil Ecology","29","2",,"173","183",,,10.1016/j.apsoil.2004.10.005,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-18144384219&partnerID=40&md5=f9555fa97709a7e1242ba7fbbbdae9f4","Inst. of Ecol. and Conserv. Biology, University of Vienna, Althanstrasse 14, A-1090 Wien, Austria; Inst. of Soil Sci. and Agrochemistry, Russian Academy of Sciences, Siberian Branch, Str. Sovetskaya 18, Novosibirsk 630099, Russian Federation","Kaiser, C., Inst. of Ecol. and Conserv. Biology, University of Vienna, Althanstrasse 14, A-1090 Wien, Austria; Meyer, H., Inst. of Ecol. and Conserv. Biology, University of Vienna, Althanstrasse 14, A-1090 Wien, Austria; Biasi, C., Inst. of Ecol. and Conserv. Biology, University of Vienna, Althanstrasse 14, A-1090 Wien, Austria; Rusalimova, O., Inst. of Soil Sci. and Agrochemistry, Russian Academy of Sciences, Siberian Branch, Str. Sovetskaya 18, Novosibirsk 630099, Russian Federation; Barsukov, P., Inst. of Soil Sci. and Agrochemistry, Russian Academy of Sciences, Siberian Branch, Str. Sovetskaya 18, Novosibirsk 630099, Russian Federation; Richter, A., Inst. of Ecol. and Conserv. Biology, University of Vienna, Althanstrasse 14, A-1090 Wien, Austria","This study examines the carbon and nitrogen stocks of soils and vegetation in different frost-boil tundra microsites (rims, troughs and bare soil patches) and aims at elucidating differences in controls of organic matter turnover. Troughs, the wettest microsite, stored the greatest part of soil C and N (23.9 and 1.7 kg m-2, respectively), while drier rims held only 50% and bare soil patches only about 17% of the C and N found in troughs. Both C and N mineralization rates were higher in rims compared to troughs, suggesting a higher turnover of organic matter in rims. On an areal basis N was predominantly mineralized in mineral horizons, while C mineralization was more or less equally distributed between organic and mineral horizons. Thus, atmospheric warming, which has a stronger effect on the upper soil layers, may increase C mineralization to a higher extent than N mineralization (mainly located in lower soil layers). This suggests that frost-boil tundra ecosystems may be (at least in the short-term) sources of CO2 to the atmosphere. Furthermore, the combined results of gross N mineralization and net N mineralization measurements showed a higher microbial sink strength for N in rims compared to troughs, suggesting that decomposition of organic material in rims is controlled mainly by N availability, while the main factor constraining decomposition in troughs may be unfavourable hydrothermal conditions. This may lead to differential responses of frost-boil tundra microsites to changing climatic conditions. © 2004 Elsevier B.V. All rights reserved.","Arctic soil; C and N storage; Global warming; Microrelief; Soil microbial biomass",,,,,,,"Amato, M., Ladd, J.N., Assay for microbial biomass based on ninhydrin-reactive nitrogen in extracts of fumigated soils (1988) Soil Biol. Biochem., 20, pp. 107-114; Amundson, R., The carbon budget in soils (2001) Annu. Rev. Earth Planet. Sci., 29, pp. 535-562; Barrett, J.E., Burke, I.C., Potential nitrogen immobilization in grassland soils across a soil organic matter gradient (2000) Soil Biol. Biochem., 32, pp. 1707-1716; Brookes, P.C., Landman, A., Pruden, G., Jenkinson, D.S., Chloroform fumigation and the release of soil nitrogen: A rapid direct extraction method to measure microbial biomass nitrogen in soil (1985) Soil Biol. Biochem., 17, pp. 837-842; (2003) Circumpolar Arctic Vegetation Map: Scale 1:7,500,000, , CAVM Team U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service Anchorage, Alaska; Chernov, Y.I., Matveyeva, N.V., Arctic ecosystems in Russia (1997) Ecosystems of the World: Polar and Alpine Tundra, 3. , F.E. Wielgolaski Elsevier Oslo, Norway; Deniss